                <div class="byline">
                    <div class="byline-author">
                        

                    
    <span class="vcard author">
    
        <a title="http://bike2work2live2bike.blogspot.com" href="http://bike2work2live2bike.blogspot.com" rel="nofollow">Ted Diamond</a>
    
    </span>


                    </div>
                    <div class="byline-date">
                        <a href="http://bikehugger.com/2007/12/should-seattle-license-cyclist.html#comment-5103"><abbr class="published" title="Permalink to this comment">December 27, 2007 &#183;  2:13 PM</abbr></a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="asset-content comment-content">
            <p>Re: &#8220;Somebody’s got an interest here and is directing the discussion&#8221;.</p>

<p>I have a much more cynical, curmudgeonly interpretation of what&#8217;s happening.  If PI-on-the-web is like a lot of other websites, its business model is to deliver reader eyeballs to advertisers, and the way to do that is to drive traffic to their site.  Cycling-related pieces, both pro- and con- have triggered, at least over the past six months, the most intense traffic in Sound-Offs.  </p>

<p>On what is supposed to be the slowest news week of the year, I can imagine the PI editorial staff trying to stimulate traffic by publishing provocative pieces that are guaranteed to get a relatively small set of stakeholders making multiple visits to the site over the course of several days to engage in the forum.</p>

<p>I can&#8217;t think of any other reason for this article to appear now.  It&#8217;s really out of the blue.</p>


